column1: 196018;instagram;2019-01-30 13:08:27;FALSE;"a happy tuesday to all you loving humans ❤️🌱
today we thought we might share with you a damiana tea recipe that we tried over the weekend.

column2: we know that damiana tea has been used for centuries in folk medicine to treat a variety of ailments
column3: most notably mild cases of constipation
column4: and also to boost libido. damiana is a gentle herb that is most frequently administered in the form of a tea or infusion. the dried leaves used to make damiana tea can be purchased at natural health stores
column5: or ordered online. this recipe yields approximately one cup of damiana tea.

column1: measure 1 or 2 heaping teaspoons of dried damiana leaves
column2: and place them into a clean coffee mug or other heat proof drinking container. bring water to boil and fill one coffee mug to just below the brim.

column1: allow the damiana tea to steep for 15-20 minutes. strain the tea into a clean coffee mug
column2: or into another heat proof drinking container. discard the spent damiana leaves in the compost pile or garbage can.
raw honey to sweeten the damiana tea
column4: but do not use granulated or refined sugar
column5: as this can damage the beneficial properties of the tea.

column1: garnish the damiana tea with a lemon wedge for additional flavor
column4: you can add 1/2 teaspoon of lemon juice.

column1: my feelings and thoughts of unworthiness are not representative of who i am. ⁣
i am more than my thoughts. ⁣

column2: trauma and relationship turmoil can all lead to feelings of being broken and ashamed.⁣

column1: often we feel encouraged to hide the pained and hurt sides of us. ⁣

column3: doesn’t place much value on the desire to be vulnerable and authentic - especially if it looks messy or hurt. ⁣

column1: so we hide these parts of ourselves

column1: our primal response isn’t wrong. being vulnerable in an un-nurturing environment could cause pain and hinder us instead of heal.⁣
for many of us our families are also not a safe place for us to be vulnerable. i can relate to that. ⁣
how can we heal and feel whole again after such experiences? ⁣
be gentle and true to yourself.
there is no race to feel whole. ⁣
wherever you are right now and however you feel - remember your thoughts and feelings are not who you are. ⁣
repeat the affirmation - i am whole. i am worthy. ⁣
you could write it down repeatedly like a written mantra or write it once and stick it up in your room. ⁣
talk to someone who is capable of holding space. someone who will listen and not judge nor try to fix you. this could be a friend
do things which get you in to your body. ⁣
i feel that there is a link between trauma and the lack of desire to exercise. moving your body
column2: moves emotions - so if you feel that you are not ready to process and move the trauma you may lack the desire to exercise. ⁣
perhaps do a gentle practice such as yin yoga or qigong or study tantra or the jade egg. ⁣

column1: 196145;instagram;2019-01-30 15:39:13;FALSE;"if you're ever lucky enough to save your innocence yourself do it. nearly everyone around me had no idea the day before this day what happened and only i and the man responsible will relive the dates like they were yesterdays days. today i relived that moment
today he stood behind me at dg and i couldnt breathe. i couldnt speak.  i couldnt type my code in. i thought for 10 years if i ever ran into that person again in my life

column2: run him over with my car
column7: or really anything ptsd related. ""say something to him jennifer"" that's all i could think but all i did is...

column1: i cried in public as i told the cashier nothing was wrong
column2: i smelled the diesel from 10 years ago in the air like someone was baking him like cookies (or i wished someone would bake his ass) or the thought of the stains under his nails touching me. the sound of his breathing while i'm having a panic attack

column1: i relived every moment of that night in 30 seconds that felt like hours  it took me back
column2: back to the day i lost myself.

column1: i still wish i would have said something anything ""pos"" ""rapist"" ""horrible human""

column1: 196153;instagram;2019-01-30 16:00:11;FALSE;"my dad kind of instilled in me a bitterness about big corporations doing charitable donations at the expense of their paying customers and getting a tax write-off for their effort in return. lol ... but this is a different kind of campaign and if bell let's talk means we can use social media and texting for some powerful conversations about mental illness? then i'm here for it.
i'm not one for being really open about myself
column2: let alone on public platforms. but i'm so sick of the stigma attached to mental illness!

column1: from the ages of 16 -21 i struggled with ""moderate"" depression and social anxiety. i self soothed and ""self medicated"" with self harm
column3: and party drugs. i was taken advantage of. yup. also #metoo. and i struggled many times with suicidal thoughts.

column1: do you see me differently now? maybe?
truth is i'm the same person. i would not be the person i am now
column2: had i not had the experiences i had then.

column1: it doesn't make me feel like i'm a stronger person now because of it
column3: making this post makes me feel really vulnerable and self conscious.

column1: i guess all i want to say is
column2: our health is something we take for granted until we are sick.  and in this ever fast passed
column4: mental illness is very common. genetics play a roll and often environmental factors act as triggers. some people get dealt some pretty shitty cards in life. and without a safe support system

column1: 196168;instagram;2019-01-30 16:08:03;FALSE;"r/p @sararradin -  i wish i could go back in time and tell 10 year old sara that she’d get to interview the lead actor of her favorite teen movie on its 20th anniversary. thank you @rachaelleighcook for speaking with me for @mtvnews!
“she's all that was one of the first teen movies i ever saw in theaters. i was 10 years old and immediately felt connected to rachael leigh cook's artsy laney boggs. i figured
column2: if she could go from being an art freak and social outcast to being pretty and popular — and win over the hottest guy in school — then maybe i could
column4: zack siler came to represent everything i assumed i should want in a man. i started to believe that if i became good looking enough and wore the right clothes
column5: i could mold myself into the attractive and submissive woman that kind of guy would want.

column1: the movies of this time period were formidable in my own coming of age experience as i consumed all kinds of messages about femininity
column4: which were always told through the male gaze. but in the wake of the #metoo and #timesup movements
column5: i’ve recently spent time re-watching many teen classics i once loved
column7: in effort to better understand how these movies shaped my self-image
column8: as well as my intimate relationships with men. seeing these films again has brought on a wave of complex emotions including nostalgia
column12: i can see how they were deeply problematic. knowing what i know now about hollywood’s gross failings
column13: is it possible to still enjoy these films? i’m honestly not sure
column14: but what i do know is that they can serve as a reminder of where things once were
column15: how far we’ve come since the 1990s
column16: and that there’s still work to be done.” - #artthot #instafamous";;en;#MeToo

column1: ok so here’s the story of how i saw this movie.
i was at the skatepark. some drunk kid
column3: was screaming at all the skateboarders and trying to get someone to fight him. it turned into a yelling match between like ten skaters and this drunk kid
column4: and i just sat back filming it all. long story short
column6: which divulged into all the skateboarders beating the shit out of this guy. like ten kids just stomping his head. brutal
column8: stuff. i just kept skating. then he says he’s gonna go get his gun and we’re all gonna die and starts walking towards his car. then the cops get there just in time and everyone just runs to their cars and speeds out of there. so i escaped and got to the movies. saw the poster to this. had no idea what it was but i was on the run so i went in
column9: and had my mind blown. forget your roma’s and blindspotting and beale streets....this is the most socially relevant film of 2018. the modern social media witch trials that have spawned from the #metoo movement
column10: and how nowadays a mere accusation can ruin a life
column11: is the foreground of this film. feminism
column16: it’s all here. assassination nation is based in salem
column17: where the witch trials began. it starts out based in reality
column18: where leaks and hacks lead to people trying to ruin others lives. then by the end jumps to extremes
column19: as everyone does when someone is accused of something
column20: and how in reality it becomes all out war with words and “cancelled” tweets.....here
column21: it’s all out war with knives
column23: and torches. it’s very reminiscent of kids
column24: and even homages kids at times. there’s fascinating conversations and debates that i wish could play in front of the world. it’s so full of style and unique
column25: bold choices. i loved the split screen scenes
column26: so full of color. this isn’t for the sensitive. it’s not for the crybabies. maybe the message is that the accused will start fighting back. those condemned to burn because someone pointed the finger and yelled
column27: “witch”! the modern day witches aren’t going to be silenced and put to death this time.";;en;#BT2018reviews

column1: 196224;instagram;2019-01-30 17:00:47;TRUE;;"i can’t express how proud i am of our new series of psas called ‘survivor stories’.

our team worked with the wonderful folks at @deutschinc and created this beautiful campaign in order to shift focus back where it belongs - on the people who actually said ‘me too.’ there are four in total. this one is close to my heart. so many men and boys have been left out of the conversation. we have to change that.
please enjoy and feel free to share!

column1: 196227;instagram;2019-01-30 17:02:55;FALSE;"what happens when men are too afraid to mentor women? that's the question maya salam explores in a recent essay published in the new york times. she reflects on an unintended consequence of the #metoo movement: companies minimizing contact between female employees and male executives
column2: effectively putting women at a disadvantage.

column1: salam points to a report by katrin bennhold
column2: who spoke with several male executives attending the annual world economic forum in davos
column3: switzerland. these men expressed concern over mentoring women today:

column1: “i now think twice about spending one-on-one time with a young female colleague
column3: speaking on the condition of anonymity because the issue is “just too sensitive.”
such as: are women now expected to cater to the fears of men who are their superiors—fears that women would ultimately pay the price for? if these men are not doing anything wrong
column4: what are they worried about? were powerful men really clamoring to help that many women before #metoo? is this behavior actually becoming commonplace
column5: or is it simply a narrow outlier expressed by a privileged few?

column1: read the full article using the link in our bio. artwork by ana galvan.

column1: 196231;instagram;2019-01-30 17:11:58;FALSE;this is uncomfortable but important i think. standing up to an abuser is tricky. i guess my point is you can achieve redemption no matter who resists your truth. i chose to listen
column2: understand and forgive. everyone has a story and those who cause harm usually were harmed. you have a choice to break the cycle. i have no interest in publicly shaming anyone or making excuses for my behavior after the trauma of that time. maybe there’s a reason why i’ve been through hell. i do have interest in being there for others. thanking the sexual assault center that i volunteered for and utilized services. they believed i did a lot of crying and healing
column3: found my true friends and repaired relationships i valued. there is life on the other side of the darkness. #sexualabuse #survivors #abuse #addiction #suicide #cyberbullying #ptsd #recovery #clean #sober #nevergiveup #bestrevengeissuccess #support #therapy #amputation #amputee #metoo #standstrong #kesha #ladygaga #sexualassaultcenter;;en;#sexualabuse

column2: i was sexually harassed/assaulted. i was on the bus
column3: sitting with bella cunningham who was a friend of my then acquaintance
column5: in the very last seat. bella cunningham decided it was a good idea to poke my breasts (yes i had them i was fucking fat
column6: ok?) repeatedly without my consent. kayla pham sat there and laughed. i didn't really know what was happening at the time and didn't realize until many years later
column7: but i had always known it was wrong. i was sitting on the inside of the seat
column8: and was pushing myself into the wall of the bus to try and get away.

column2: my assault/harassment came from a girl. it's not only boys who harass
column3: assault and rape. when i told my doctor
column4: she automatically assumed it was a boy who touched me.

column2: but it's still harassment. it truly affected the way i dressed in that i wore sweatshirts ever since then. it wasn't until 7th grade when i stopped wearing them constantly. i had even gotten used to the heat of sweatshirts because that's how much i wore them. everytime time i left my house
column3: i made sure to wear a sweatshirt. i would always hide my chest. it's gotten to the point where when i make characters to draw
column4: they had to go through a similar trauma just so i could be open about it yet secretive
column5: so that no one would know
column6: but this way i could tell people in a subtle way. it even made me hate hugs
column7: because my chest would touch someone else's. recently
column8: i've gotten through that barrier a little. but please always ask before you hug me
column9: but side hugs are (almost always) ok. i'll tell you if i'm comfort able with them when/if i ask for a side hug from you
column10: then feel free to give me one anytime
column11: but only if i've told you specifically that its ok to do so anytime.

column1: 196251;instagram;2019-01-30 17:16:33;FALSE;"rp @anonymous___activism - a mother crying for her stolen baby.

those who lie to you and tell you animals don’t feel are the same ones who profit from them. those who exploit mothers and slaughter children are the same ones who try to convince us that cows breastfeeding milk belongs to us and not to their babies.
those who have been manipulating us for years telling us that human adults need calcium from someone else’s mother’s milk and that they « magically » produce it without having to give birth.

today we say no to dairy because we choose to stop listening to those who have been lying to us forcing us to participate in something cruel that we never wanted to take part in. and we decide to side with the victims of this atrocity instead.

column1: 196303;instagram;2019-01-30 18:00:24;FALSE;"level up: i’m moving into my own studio in [redacted]* this friday
column2: affording me the chance to introvert the fuck out as i please 😈. it’s been awesome living the luxury life in midtown this past year. it was everything i could’ve asked for
column3: and more—truly the most supportive environment as i struggled to survive.

column1: when i was barely mobile due to super bruised rib and other assault injuries
column2: they were there to play dominion with me. when i was beyond panicky/outraged due to getting framed for felony and cops coming after me
column3: they were there to talk/listen to me. when i turned myself in
column4: they were there on standby to bail me out if needed. when i was getting harassed in my own apt by a private investigator hired by my abuser
column5: they were there to tell her to fuck off. when i had to practice testifying with the da
column6: they were there to listen to me trauma-complain afterward.

column3: i’ll miss the engagement photo shoots with lil wiener dog 💜

196317;instagram;2019-01-30 18:23:25;FALSE;today is #bellletstalkday and so i figure it's a good day to share my story. (2013) in grade 6 is when i first really started struggling with depression. i found that i was losing all my motivation and i couldn't sleep. i started falling behind in school and i developed my first eating disorder. (2014) things just got progressively worse. i became so hard to hangout with and my friends started to notice. self harm became a reality for me.(2015) i had my first suicide attempt. i lost friends. i couldn't function on my own anymore. i would just fall apart. i didnt sleep. i wouldnt let my self eat at all if i could avoid it. i started taking my unhappiness and confusion out on my friends. my relationship with my siblings started to fall apart. (2016) i had my first boyfriend and i valued myself so little that in the end everyone got hurt. i viewed myself like what happened to me didn't matter. i lost a close friend to suicide which caused me to blame myself. i started hurting myself daily. and i attempted 4 or 5 times seriously. i got assaulted in oct in 2016 and it was a big deal. i couldn't speak about it. i felt so sick and terrified for days. this was when i was introduced to ptsd. (2017) things were pretty bad. i lost the guy and it was a huge deal and a very messy situation. i was so angry. i fought with my family constantly. i started questioning everything. i started doing dumb things. i started going to therapy and taking medications.

(2018) i spent a lot of this year in the hospital. i was in almost weekly for months. i was hospitalized. i couldn't eat for months without getting sick. when i started to be able to eat i gained a ton of weight so my self confidence dropped to like 0. in the summer things eased up a bit and then i got injured. it was like my whole world ended. i had surgery to repair it and started recovery but i fell really far behind in everything. (2019)  i went into this year determined to make a change. we are only a month in and i never would've guessed i would make it to where i am today. i am so proud of myself. i know now that i can make a difference and that i matter! mental health made me who i am. and this was my journey so far";;en;#bellletstalkday;;;;;0;;a_jjackson;Abbie;;0;False;6;0;0;81;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/6215edc92015101bee0dd7cd155f0e0c/5D099A1A/t51.2885-15/e35/50667502_1268410579965461_3406246715577126074_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"today is #bellletstalkday and so i figure it is a good day to share my story. (2014) things just got progressively worse. i became so hard to hangout with and my friends started to notice. self harm became a reality for me.(2015) i had my first suicide attempt. i lost friends. i couldn't function on my own anymore. i would just fall apart. i didnt sleep. i wouldnt let my self eat at all if i could avoid it. i started taking my unhappiness and confusion out on my friends. my relationship with my siblings started to fall apart. (2016) i had my first boyfriend and i valued myself so little that in the end everyone got hurt. i viewed myself like what happened to me didn't matter. i lost a close friend to suicide which caused me to blame myself. i started hurting myself daily. and i attempted 4 or 5 times seriously. i got assaulted in oct in 2016 and it was a big deal. i couldn't speak about it. i felt so sick and terrified for days. this was when i was introduced to ptsd. column1: the most eye opening and surprising information i’ve thought differently about recently is how my black neighbours and community members move through the world. there’s the horrendous police brutality or the total lack of accountability for perpetrators of violence against the black community. what was really  jarring for me was the news cycle of black folks having the police called on them for literally living their lives. when i used to hear members of the black community say “just existing is a crime if you’re black”
column2: i used to nod my head but i had no idea how literal it was! then i’m seeing black folks getting police called on them for having bbqs
column5: college students napping in the common room. and it floored me that it was absolutely as literal as i was hearing it. i used to really keep to myself in my community. but now
column6: i at least try to be a more active witness. even just standing by
column7: ready to film a situation or provide corroboration if needed.

column1: i think probably the me too movement. as a muslim woman who has never worn a hijab
column2: i’m not sure how islamophobia has really changed on the daily in my community. but as a woman
column3: i have noticed a huge shift in the wake of the me too movement. even my male friends used to think our fears
column4: experiences or feelings were pretty wildly exaggerated. i’ve noticed more listening. less eye rolls. more open ended questions. i have to do far less convincing.

column1: i think being a citizen is about consideration and accessibility. i always want to be voting or contributing to my community not from where i sit or what i want but from where my community members who may be harmed by this decision are sitting. if everyone voted with the most vulnerable members of their community in mind
column4: true care. because i’m a social worker
column5: being a citizen to me means making community accessible. looking around and saying “who’s not here?” in toronto we still have so many public transit vehicles that aren’t wheelchair accessible. we should know why. and then we should make a plan to correct it.";;en;;;;;;0;;thecitizeninstitute;The Citizen Institute;;0;False;1;0;0;27;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/ea32bad9574ab4336846fcc56437eb43/5D1398E6/t51.2885-15/e35/50100430_635178463564100_7664533140168250198_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"interview 4: sara k.

column1: growing up sex has been a topic that was never brought up in many african homes.

do you all remember the 'bold and the beautiful' and the many times we would watch a movie or the soap operas with our parents but when suddenly a sex scene comes on which always seemed to drag on forever??🤔🤔 there was always an awkward silence as everyone tries to find the remote control ashamed to be in the presence of such a scene😐
the sad truth is that even if they didn't teach us we eventually learnt it elsewhere either to our damage or not.

column2: we are in times where we are a sexually charged generation
column3: a society where sex is at the forefront of everything that sells and the topic sex should not be a taboo no more
column4: because it would be soo sad finding out that your daughter was sexually assaulted and never turned to you or some young girls comes to your home and accuses your son for raping them just because you didn't teach them on what is right or wrong in the name ""sex is for grown ups""

column1: with the #metoo movement and all the awareness to sexual abuse and harassment
column2: there’s no better time for a movie like the tale. it’s a remarkable and effective depiction of sexual abuse and its effect on women that i never want to watch again.

column1: the tale is the cinematic memoir of writer and director jennifer fox about her own childhood sexual abuse. it even opens with a warning: “the story you’re about to see is true... as far as i know.” that is
column2: because the film is also (and mainly) about memory and memory’s unreliability. fox dramatises a traumatising real-life experience and the stories she told herself in order to survive that and get past it. so the beauty of the film is in showing how messy and slippery our memories work
column3: especially when feeling differently about an event that we remember in a different way.

column1: laura dern is the one responsible for the incarnation of fox (who gives the character her real name) as an adult. and as a lifelong fan of dern
column2: i can say this is the performance of her lifetime. she has the tough job of being on the head-space of someone realising a harsh
column4: piece by piece. and she nails it; you can see the articulation of her confusion
column5: emotions and conflicting thoughts in her eyes in every scene.

column2: who’s best known as a documentary filmmaker
column3: she uses some of the genre’s devices in the tale
column4: making it more of an autobiographical film due to the interactions between her adult self and her thirteen year old self. straight-to-camera speeches
column5: games of temporal disjunction and moments when the narrator/protagonist interacts directly with her younger self and people still in the past are also used to express the fragility of memory yet that we’re watching a true story nonetheless.

column1: i would like to take a moment to acknowledge the struggle of maintaining a focus on our well-being. i myself have felt a sense from well-meaning friends and family that once i embark on the journey to recovery as a survivor and someone with persistent mental health issues
i admit i contribute to this feeling by putting pressure on myself internally to always improve my state of being. but by default
column2: this does not allow for the natural ups and downs of emotional well-being. if we acknowledge that our mental state continuously fluctuates
column3: then it should logically follow that the path to mindful self-care fluctuates as well.

column1: just because we step into a therapist’s office
column2: does not automatically mean things are all good. it means we have taken the first step by acknowledging and accepting that we could use some help/guidance/support.

column1: a reminder to myself and my peers that no one dictates my well-being and it is incumbent upon myself to be kind and supportive to me.

column1: for years i told myself that i wasn’t worthy of any of any love. how could anyone love me when i was raped and molested?
how could anyone love me because i was bullied so bad at school.
i told myself i was garbage and worthless. i was set on believing that i deserved what happened to me because why would such bad things happen to a good person?
growing up in a some-what religious house hold
column2: i convinced myself that i was being punished by god.

column1: at the age of 3 i was molested several times by my grandfather. the husband of my very religious grandmother. while she told me god forgave him for his actions
column2: she never told me i was forgiven. i was ashamed.

column1: that’s when i decided i wasn’t worthy of love. god didn’t love me
column2: so no one else could. including myself.

column1: at the age of 5 those feelings became so strong that i started to turn to food to comfort them. as i grew older
column2: this became my ritual for comfort and self-destruction.

column1: food made me feel safe. i hid my true self
column2: tucked away under layers of junk food and body fat. i buried myself so deep
column3: that no one could find me. my fat became my emotional bubble wrap.

column2: and because of my lack of self-love
column3: my son almost died. my weight had skyrocketed to the point where i could hardly play with my him. he ran from me at the park and was almost hit by car as he ran through the gate and into the street. i could not catch a 3 year old child.

column1: that day was the catalyst to my transformation. i realized i am loved. by my son
column3: my family. i was gifted with love and i almost lost it all because of my lack of self-worth. .

column1: that day i came home and wrote on my mirror
this act became and still is a daily practice of self-love for me. that day as i wrote those words
column3: it was the first time i believed them. as i write these words today
column4: i am reminded of why i need to love-myself.

column3: and for you. i know now my experiences as terrible as they were
column4: are gifts. through them i learned to love-myself fully

column1: 196468;instagram;2019-01-30 20:59:34;FALSE;"""dweller in the valley: wounds of an emerging queen"" dropping march 2019 . . . thank you to everybody that has supported me along the way. this journey has really been eye-opening and it has helped me become who i am. i hope that the story in this book can help some women. if you have been in a toxic relationship than this book is for you. if you have dealt with issues in the legal system than this book is for you. if you have ever felt backstabbed and felt like giving up as a result then this book is for you. i'm here for you and i love you so much. thanks for all of the support as i've been on this writing journey. #anathelifecoach #respect #honor #honorcode #source #culture #agreement #professional #word #wordisbond #author #success";;en;#AnaTheLifeCoach

column1: 196470;instagram;2019-01-30 21:00:36;FALSE;"“i bought vip tickets to a high profile event for my boyfriend for his birthday. i bought a gorgeous outfit that made me feel like i was working a red carpet. the event was in las vegas so i felt a little freedom to be ‘extra’ (although tbh i don’t have many qualms being ‘extra’ in daily life
column2: just felt more acceptable there especially). the tickets were thousands of dollars so naturally we were surrounded mostly by people with a good amount of expendable income. after the event
column3: we were walking around the most expensive/elite area. every guy there was in a flashy expensive suit with designer shoes and done up hair. as i walked with my boyfriend through the crowd
column4: a guy who couldn’t have been older that 35 scanned my body with his eyes
column5: turned to his friend and shouted “holy shit
column6: check out the tits on this one!” i was so shocked and angry. for some reason it felt so unexpected to me that i might be harassed so blatantly in a crowd that was mostly well-educated and wealthy-- though i know now the issue is much more than a threat from one socioeconomic group. my boyfriend felt angry and helpless as well-- but both of us were too shocked to do anything. we kept walking
column7: shaken. after about thirty seconds i was full of ideas about how i could have or should have responded to the situation to embarrass that asshole or catch him off guard in return. he did that because he knew he could get away with it and i wish i knew how to show him he fucking can’t. i am still embarrassed today that i was too embarrassed in the moment to snap back at him. this happened two and a half years ago. i still lay in bed trying to sleep thinking of things to do and say in the face of that harassment so that i don’t just passively walk away next time.” - @laurentheyoung

column2: send your stories to catscallingback@gmail.com or dm me. •

column2: i wasn’t comfortable opening up to people about my struggles with my mental health. and
column3: i can’t say i am completely comfortable with it now either. i’m not going to bore you with the details
column4: but i’ll give it to you in a nutshell. growing up
column7: considering my severe inability to cope in everyday situations. shit
column8: i couldn’t even order a meal at mcdonald’s on my own. i also struggle with depression
column9: which is something i’m even more uncomfortable speaking about. however
column10: something incredibly heartbreaking that happens way too often happened to me at the end of my second year of college (which is an entire other societal issue that has seen the spotlight recently in the #metoo movement). i dealt with my pain and need to regain control of myself and my own body in ways that were dangerous to myself and others. the real breaking point was my inability to sleep; i slept an average of 2 hours every night for a very long time because my mind just would not stop. i have a few friends that know the shitty details of this situation and the more intensified mental health issues that followed
column13: i’m the same girl as i am in this picture. and ultimately
column15: i realized that i didn’t have to do this on my own. i didn’t have to suffer in silence. counselling helped
column16: but medication helped even more. it’s been a long road
column17: but this time two years ago i wasn’t sleeping at night and i most certainly was not in the mental state to begin travelling like i have been. now
column18: here i am! healthier than ever! ready to bust down doors and take on the world.

column1: 196496;instagram;2019-01-30 21:08:21;FALSE;"i remember dating a guy in high school who tried to push the limits on what i was comfortable with
column2: physically speaking. i didn't really know what to do
column3: how to assert myself or even what was ""normal"". so after one encounter that i wasn't sure i was okay with
column4: i found myself in the bathroom asking ""did i really want that to happen? but i didn't say no or anything so i guess that means it was okay.""

column1: last week's post was all about how to teach kids about consent so they can avoid what happened to me as a teenager. this week
column2: i want to dig deeper about what consent really means. and how i believe christians should be the ones setting the standard on how to live it out.

column1: when we peel back the layers to better understand what consent really is
column2: it makes applying what seems to be a difficult concept much easier. all the intricacies in deciding what is appropriate or not starts to fade when we embrace that consent is not a set of rules and contracts but rather respecting another person’s humanity and valuing their identity as a child of god. having those rules helps
column3: for sure! but it has to start by valuing and respecting a person's humanity first. .

column1: because when we can do this
column2: we can reach more people with the message of the gospel. we can build bridges and create relationships. when we see people as human beings with a soul
column3: we are then able to apply the concepts of consent so much easier because we are starting from the foundational level of what it really means.

column1: 196548;instagram;2019-01-30 22:24:39;FALSE;"it’s #bellletstalk day and opening the conversation on mental health and breaking the stigma associated with it is super important to us! 💜 5 things to remember not just today but every day.
1. there is nothing wrong with asking for help. there’s nothing to be ashamed of when seeing a counsellor/therapist.
2. your experiences matter! whether big or small to you
column2: remember you can talk about it. your feelings are valid.

column1: 3. your friends aren’t your punching bags or professional therapists
column2: remember that we are all going thru it!!! empathize
column3: ask if it’s okay before completely sharing what you’re going through. not everyone’s in the right space to listen/help but it doesn’t mean you’re not deserving of help.

column1: 4. your mental health is just as important as your physical health! say no to negative self talk
column2: say no to pessimistic friends and people who don’t believe in your journey.

column1: 5. love love love. check in on people you love and make sure you’re one of those people. no one is perfect and it is an unfair expectation to think you have to be. self love is the best kind of love you’ll never run out of.❤️ — with love

today is #bellletstalk day so this is my video to finally open up about the parts of me that you don't see in my online personality. it's not all smiles and sunshine (although i try to make it like that as much as i can).

this is not meant to be a #metoo video; i didn't do this to add my voice to the many others calling for change (although i fully support he movement and wish all those people the best). i made this video for #me and my own healing
i don't talk about it enough in this video but therapy has been a huge help in getting me to the point where i could make this video and share my story. if you feel alone or lost
column2: remember that you aren't. if you need someone to talk to
column3: please feel free to message me but i also urge you to get professional help and unlock some of the secret burdens you might be carrying.

column1: new one from the series! i told you i would share the meaning behind the pieces.. so get ready for some of my thoughts.

for me this piece doesn't have any facial details because it is not based off of one specific girl. instead she remains faceless because it represents more than just one girl. it represents all girls growing up and the transition from girl to women. .

column2: this is my story as it pertains to this piece: .

column1: for me growing up i never felt the need to be on guard of my gender or discuss its impact on my chosen career or life.
it wasn't until later that i realized that sexism was still present in our society. .

when i was in gr.8 wearing a ""man up"" t-shirt from nike playing soccer with my class. i hadn't realized the implications and greater meaning to what that really meant. i just wanted to show i was as ""tough"" as the boys and could hold my own ground. .

it wasn't until i joined a summer painting company and heard the vp of the company tell one of the senior managers that he had hired another female manager for our area because he was ""going to get him laid this summer"" .
it wasn't until i was having a conversation with an older woman who encouraged me to take a full time job instead of pursuing my art because ""what if i wanted to have children one day?"" .
it wasn't until a family member was telling me i needed to wear an apron to do the dishes because ""i need to learn to be a good house wife"" .

it wasn't until later that i learned about the gender pay gap. it wasn't until later that i learned about the #metoo movement and all of the women coming forward to share stories of what had happened to them. it wasn't until later that i learned the statistics on sexual assault. .

it wasn't until later that i had start wearing a ""steel dress"" to block the negative and out dated beliefs of how women should behave. realizing we are not victims but we are going to change the world in kick ass crazy awesome ways because we are women! .

it wasn't until i joined a summer painting company and heard the vp of the company tell one of the senior managers that he had hired another female manager for our area because he was ""going to get him laid this summer"" .
it wasn't until i was having a conversation with an older woman who encouraged me to take a full time job instead of pursuing my a because ""what if i wanted to have children one day?"" .
it wasn't until a family member was telling me i needed to wear an apron to do the dishes because ""i need to learn to be a good house wife"" .

it wasn't until later that i learned about the gender pay gap. it wasn't until later that i learned about the  movement and all of the women coming forward to share stories of what had happened to them. it wasn't until later that i learned the statistics on sexual assault. .

it wasn't until later that i had sta wearing a ""steel dress"" to block the negative and out dated beliefs of how women should behave. realizing we are not victims but we are going to change the world in kick ass crazy awesome ways because we are women! .

column3: menilai alasan tingginya angka kekerasan seksual di indonesia yang menjadi latar belakang legalisasi rancangan undang undang (ruu) penghapusan kekerasan seksual (pks) sungguh mengada-ada.

bukan sekadar ada umbrella act lalu persoalan kekerasan seksual selesai. perancis yang telah mengatur tentang sanksi kriminal pelecehan seksual di tempat kerja menunjukkan pejabat dunia christine lagarde yang juga mantan menkeu pransis pernah menjadi korban pelecehan seksual bersama puluhan mantan perempuan terkemuka prancis lainnya. atau gerakan #metoo yang kini mendunia menunjukkan bahwa hukum di negara-negara tersebut tidak mampu menghentikan kekerasan seksual.

column1: pratma lalu mengungkap tiga alasan kalangan feminis ngotot ingin melegalisasi ruu pks
column2: “pertama menyuburkan perilaku sekuler liberal. muatan srhr (sexual and reproductive healths rights) sebagai ‘amanah’ beijing platform for action (bpfa) amat kuat. frasa ‘kontrol seksual’ itu menegaskan daulat atas tubuh sehingga seorang istri berhak menolak hamil atau menolak ajakan suaminya ke tempat tidur. termasuk hak untuk meluapkan orientasi seksual pada apapun atau siapapun.”

column3: merusak keluarga terutama relasi suami istri. tak ada lagi qawwam (pemimpin) dalam rumah tangga termasuk dalam hubungan yang amat privat. ketiga
column5: dengan dukungan negara leluasa mengadvokasi umat untuk tidak lagi patuh pada hukum allah.

column1: “menjadi keharusan bagi kaum muslimin untuk menolak dan mencegah kemunkaran ini dengan aksi nyata
pratma kemudian menjelaskan bahwa umat islam harus berupaya menegakkan syariat islam kaffah sebagai solusi persoalan kekerasan terhadap perempuan
column2: “tidak kalah penting mengedukasi umat bahwa persoalan kekerasan seksual
column3: bahkan pelecehan kehormatan perempuan tak akan terjadi jika khilafah tegak. syariat kaffah itu memiliki hukum yang amat memuliakan manusia apalagi perempuan dengan hukum-hukum sistem pergaulannya
column4: ” tukasnya.";;en;#Metoo;;;;;0;;nazlia_fn;Ummu Al Ghozi;;0;False;0;0;0;37;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/dd4cacbc23b9e85dc490ce892e24d35e/5D1AB600/t51.2885-15/e35/50024282_2320271204919839_99147765650051708_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"muslimahnews.com — pengamat politik dan pemerhati perempuan

column1: 196663;instagram;2019-01-31 01:06:39;FALSE;"today is #bellletstalk so here is my truth. ▶️
it has been 1 year and almost 5 months since i lost my best childhood friend. ▶️
it was a violent shooting cause by a man who couldn’t accept that his ex-wife wanted to be treated fairly. so he killed 8 people in her home and my best friend was one of them. ▶️
i was sexually assaulted in my own home. ▶️
i was laughed at when i explained to a friend what happened. ▶️
i’ve felt alone and helpless. i’ve cried for hours on end only to stop because i’m dehydrated and can’t cry anymore. ▶️
i’m here because of a number of things i’d like to share.
1. i opened up. it lessened the feeling of being alone. i also heard others stories which comforted me more than i realized they could.
2. i went to therapy. i still do. it allows me to re-train my mind to shift my thinking in a safe space. the things i’ve learned i wished i had been taught at a much earlier age.
3. i wrote music. i expressed my emotions. whatever you enjoy doing
column5: coding. do something you love and pour your heart into it.

column1: i wrote my most recent song after 3 sleepless weeks. i had to share what i felt like and how nothing anyone does can make it better. i realized only after writing that “speaking my truth” through song is why my song became so therapeutic for me. my song is my truth and i’m sharing so you know you’re not alone. 💟what’s your truth⁉️";;en;#bellletstalk;;;;;0;;haleydemosmusic;Haley Demos Music;;0;False;3;0;0;46;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/6b94b13820b2845600c6db06a4dbd680/5D268546/t51.2885-15/e35/50128954_1158356694328206_4123138870189387519_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"today is #bellletstalk so here is my truth. ▶️

column1: i don't know how broken i will be when i meet you
column3: but i am writing this letter to you.

column1: this isn't the list of things you should be
column2: because this isn't a slam book
column3: where you write about the perfect guy. i am not writing this to you
column5: just like you prepare yourself for an examination. because
column6: you can never be prepared for love
column7: since it has no prescribed syllabus.

column1: i just want you to know that when you come into my life
column2: help me pick up all the pieces of it. by then
column3: there will be too many for me to pick up. alone. i want you to believe in me then
column4: even  in my worst state. and accept me the way i am. accept me with my scars
column6: and do not heal them. just be proud of them

column1: i do not want you to heal my broken heart
column2: because i can do it myself once i pick up the pieces.

column3: with no one by my side
column4: i want to believe in you. because
column6: would lead me to belive myself.

column1: maybe you don't exist. maybe you are just a reassuring mirage in a desert. yet you are a reminder that the oasis does exist.
and even if you don't exist

column1: 196667;instagram;2019-01-31 01:09:28;FALSE;"i know in my recent posts you can obviously see self harm scars on my legs. i know i used to have a big account and presence in the chicago creative community and disappeared. i was abused and raped by someone prominent in the community and too afraid to speak. on top of it i have bipolar disorder onset by ptsd from previous things that happened in my life. i used to think “why me?” with all the pills i take daily and treatments but most days i no longer do. i’m not ashamed to show my scars in my photos nor my story. i’m not afraid to go on vacation anymore and where a swim suit or shorts. i want anyone who’s experienced trauma to not be afraid and know it gets better. this man in this picture is my husband and has saved my life. he has a hell of a story too but no matter what we support each other. without him i can’t even imagine having a career or roof over my head. he’s the bright part of my day and if you personally are going through something know that there is someone out there good hearted and pure who will understand you.

column1: 196699;instagram;2019-01-31 01:38:25;FALSE;"electricat no. ! enamel pins available at the link in my bio.

the skull and crossbones is an iconic design that has resonated with people across generations in the morbid freedom of the pirate. i designed this at a low point in my life i’m still trying to get out of. i used the money i made from selling the collection of work by an artist i admired who assaulted and harassed people i knew and came after me when i confronted him. the pin didn’t sell well because i lost confidence in myself. electricat in concept and in this design is a fight against the systemic ways our voices are either suppressed
column3: or outright ignored. it’s an effort to survive as an artist when you can’t trust the gatekeepers. it’s a process of learning to trust people again. it’s an attempt at optimism from darkness.

column1: the people who were the most helpful to me during my darkest periods were not the ones who ignored my suffering and pretended everything was fine
column2: nor were they the ones at the other end of the spectrum who tried to “fix” everything.  they were the ones who showed up. who created a safe space for me
column3: and who met me where i was. they were the ones who said
column4: “i see you. i love you. you are not alone.”

column1: i’m so grateful for the people who were willing to get uncomfortable. who sat by my side
column3: and listened with open hearts. who saw the good in me and reminded me of it. and who helped me make my way through

column1: 196762;instagram;2019-01-31 02:51:06;FALSE;honesty time: i've taken a few steps back recently. i've really struggled with self-harming again. i've been having a series of nightmares to do with my rape. when i'm in this pit
column2: honestly it feels like a merry go round and i'm never going to get out of this hole. i have been told to just change my mindset but i think this is a massive misconception. depression is a mental illness and if i could just change the way i think and control my adrenaline to not reach for a blade then trust me
column3: i would. not to mention wearing jeans in this heat is an absolute bitch. i'm trying though
column4: i'm giving myself grace that it's okay for me to fall back a little
column5: this doesn't make me a failure it just means i need to be a little more gentle with myself. i can't control the circumstances around me but i can control how i deal with them. dealing with everything efficiently rather than stewing over it has been my key recently. it allows me to free up some space to focus on my mental health. not holding grudges has also been key. just letting things go is allowing me to sleep and repair my body as mental illness drains you physically and not just mentally. sometimes we need to take a few steps to find our reset buttons
column6: focus on your cognitive behaviour therapy and figure out our methods to deal with things. i'm okay

column3: or at least you should. the manchester-based dance-rock act truly embody the idea of doing the most
column5: of going over the top. their self-titled debut got them pegged as a boy band because of their younger
column7: but it also had the seeds of what they’d soon become. those seeds started to sprout on 2016’s i like it when you sleep
column8: for you are so beautiful yet so unaware of it — whose absurd mouthful of a title reflected the grandiose ambitions of the album itself. lead singer matt healy leaned into his group’s emo and post-punk inspirations but wrapped everything in glossy pop tones and incorporated r&b and adult contemporary idioms. the expanded sonic palette and larger-than-life aspirations paid off
column9: winning the 1975 adulation from new listeners and genuine admiration from critics. their third full-length
column10: produced by healy and drummer george daniel
column11: shouldn’t work on paper. it’s got yet another crazy title
column12: a brief inquiry into online relationships
column13: and its actual release was preceded by five singles and a 24-page manifesto. healy even talked about how their upcoming record needed to be his group’s own the queen is dead or ok computer. huge expectations to live up to
column14: but the 1975 deliver on them. a brief inquiry shoots for the moon
column15: and its landing is almost as era-defining as neil armstrong’s. the lp still has one foot in the ‘80s
column16: but its catholic embrace of contemporary styles (trop house and trap hi-hats
column17: glitch-hop and britpop) and panoramic gaze upon modern culture (kanye west and donald trump
column19: black lives matter and #metoo) make it a perfect encapsulation of our zeitgeist. what takes it from simply timely to timeless
column21: is healy’s honest appraisal of his own humanity. the singer checked himself into rehab shortly after the 1975 began work on a brief inquiry
column22: and it’s the reality of getting clean — not the romance of being a rockstar — that ensures we’ll be listening to this lp for years to come.";;en;#46

column1: dr. kristen mark of psychology today shares the three main take-home messages we can learn from studying sexual response cycles:
✔ sexual pleasure and satisfaction aren't reliant on orgasm...though orgasm may certainly be a nice bonus.
✔ sexual desire doesn't always have to come before sexual activity or arousal...sometimes getting physical and experiencing arousal will elicit desire.
✔ external factors such as relationship dynamics
column3: and weighing rewards and costs of sexual experience may play an important role in sexual response.

column1: 196885;instagram;2019-01-31 04:47:51;FALSE;"holding sacred space for another to heal- i’m sharing this with his permission
tonight i had a client that the last time he went to a sexual healer she abused him
i let him know…my body doesn’t get involved
column2: i don’t get naked with my clients
column3: this is all about you and your healing. i am a healer first

column1: i asked him if it was ok to enter his energy field to read whatever is ready to be let go of
column2: he said yes….as permission and consent is vital. he looked at me and said “i trust you
column3: i feel safe with you”. i felt honored. he told me he chose me from all the stories i wrote on facebook and how i had gained trust with him and treated his with dignity in every interaction. i told him i rarely work with men
column4: but something told me to work with him. so i said yes to it.

column1: i could tell shortly into the session he was ready to release so much and to heal. it felt like the universe was swirling inside of him and releasing through bright white light! my hands grew very hot
column3: and the colors that came in to support him to heal
column4: were bright and brilliant and full of radiance!

column1: i felt his late beloved come in and all the cords that bound each other in such a deep rich love…and how it was time to let go. though
column3: i asked him if it was ok to disconnect the cords…as i wanted to make sure he was ready…if they’d disconnect. he said yes. i felt the presence of his beloved in the room
column4: i felt her willingness to let him go and be free…she wanted him to love again and to be back in his bliss with a beloved. cord by cord
column5: core by core…which the two main ones were heavy like stones
column6: and a few lighter ones…released and went down into the earth again to dissolve. only a few remained to support him to love and to remember the love they shared.

column1: i saw that part of his heart needed some light to support him in softening around another loss of his life…and as that softened i felt this request come through…and i asked the universe to bring back all the broken parts that he has let go of or

column2: ” a documentary that details sexual abuse allegations against michael jackson
column3: premiered recently at the sundance film festival. the documentary
column5: focuses on the abuse allegations of wade robson and james safechuck who both say jackson abused them when they were aged 7 and 10. angry fans tried to get the film pulled from the festival citing that it features uncorroborated allegations and the jackson estate has denounced the film releasing a statement calling it a “lurid production in an outrageous and pathetic attempt to exploit and cash in on michael jackson.” jackson denied all abuse allegations while he was alive. the film will air later this year on hbo.

column1: shannon sturges shares her experiences and insight on working in the film industry
i tried to do other things
column2: but i kept coming back to acting. i love the art form. many people don’t appreciate the art of acting. you can use your whole life experience
column4: and your body. you can inspire
column6: heal and change people and yourself.

column1: what inspired you to become a professional acting coach?
i think that it was a natural progression
column2: wanting to share with other actors what i’d learned. i also had the most amazing teacher
column5: who encouraged me to teach. he recognized that i had a gift for it and nurtured that in our over 30 years working together.

column1: after the #metoo received a lot of press
column2: women have noticed more opportunities for women. still
column3: there’s more work to do. what are your thoughts?

column1: i don’t believe that the #metoo movement has increased opportunities for women
column2: but i hope that it was helping to alert the industry to bad behavior and let women (and men) know that they have a voice when they might have felt helpless. i do believe that awareness and shedding light on these practices will lessen the pervasive nature of these situations.

column1: 196906;instagram;2019-01-31 05:47:41;FALSE;"‘we are dying from overthinking. we are slowly killing ourselves by thinking about everything. think. think. think. you can never trust the human mind anyway. it's a death trap.’
how to stop your mind from eating you alive:
in this society we tent to overthink
column2: overanalyse and therefore forget how it was to be a child. how to see the world unfiltered but instead with great curiosity and excitement.

column1: i admit that i get caught up in my own thoughts way too easily. i say things to myself i wouldn’t think about anyone else and in the past i desperately tried to control every little thing in my life and if things wouldn’t go as expected i thought my life was going to end (literally). usually that’s the time i did (and still do) some (or all) of these things:
✨ i put some music in and go for a walk. music and nature always put me in another headspace
column2: make my imagination go wild and put me in the mood for creating.

column1: ✨ talking about creating: express yourself. paint
column2: even if you think you suck at it
column3: sing even if your voice breaks at high notes
column4: or just put some music on and dance. i love little ecstatic dance sessions in my room. motion creates emotion
column5: so shaking all that negative shit off really helps.

column1: ✨ talk to someone. in the past whenever i was in a really f*ed up headspace i would call my best friend. the urge to harm yourself passes
column3: you just have to give yourself time to breathe.

column1: ✨ talking about breathing: meditate. always. okay.

column3: take care of yourself. as simple as this might sound to some in the past these were huge challenges. but regardless if you want to leave your bed or not: simple acts of self love go a long way. ✨ make yourself a good meal or a cup of tea. and read. books are a refuge.

column1: ✨ establish a routine that works for you. these were just a few things that helped and still help me. find your own routine.
and lastly: know that you are so
column2: so incredible worthy. that you are loved. and that sensitivity is not a flaw
column3: even if society likes to label emotions as a weakness.
